## Chapter 1: The Case for Equity: Historical Facts and Media Fiction

### "Everybody Ought to Be Rich"

- August 1929: **John J. Raskob**, chairman of Democratic National Committee, published "Everybody Ought to Be Rich" in *Ladies' Home Journal*
- Claimed $15/month invested in stocks would grow to $80,000 in 20 years through compound interest
- Timing was catastrophic: article appeared two months before **Great Crash of 1929**
- Despite the crash, Raskob's arithmetic was correct—he underestimated stock returns
- $15/month from 1929–1949 would have accumulated to $8,500, not $80,000, but still a 13% annual return
- Same strategy continued through 1999 would have yielded over $1 million

> "Not only can one become rich, but ought to do so." — John J. Raskob

### Asset Returns Since 1802

- **Jeremy Siegel** compiled comprehensive data on stocks, bonds, bills, gold, and dollar returns from 1802 to present
- Real returns (after inflation) show remarkable stability across two centuries
- Stocks: 6.6–7% real annual return over entire period
- Bonds: 3.5–3.6% real return
- Treasury bills: 2.7–2.9% real return
- Gold: nearly zero real return over long periods
- Dollar purchasing power: declined 95% since 1802 due to inflation

### Historical Perspectives on Stocks as Investments

#### The Influence of Smith's Work

- **Edgar Lawrence Smith**'s 1924 book *Common Stocks as Long-Term Investments* was groundbreaking
- Demonstrated stocks outperformed bonds over long periods—contrary to conventional wisdom
- **John Maynard Keynes** praised Smith's work in 1925, calling it "most important" for investors
- Before Smith, stocks were considered speculation; bonds were "investments"
- Smith showed corporate earnings growth and dividend reinvestment created wealth bonds couldn't match

#### Irving Fisher's "Permanently High Plateau"

- **Irving Fisher**, Yale economist, declared stocks had reached "permanently high plateau" in October 1929
- Statement made days before market crash—became infamous example of poor timing
- Fisher was early advocate of index investing and stock superiority
- His reputation destroyed by crash, but his fundamental analysis was sound
- Long-term data vindicated Fisher's thesis despite short-term disaster

#### A Radical Shift in Sentiment

- Pre-1920s: stocks viewed as risky speculation compared to "safe" bonds
- 1920s: **Smith** and **Fisher** shifted thinking toward stocks as wealth-building tools
- 1929 crash reversed sentiment temporarily but didn't change underlying economics
- Post-WWII: stocks gradually regained favor among institutions
- 1950s: dividend yields fell below bond yields for first time—signaled permanent shift in perception

#### The Postcrash View of Stock Returns

- 1930s–1940s: deep skepticism about stocks persisted
- Many investors who bought in 1929 didn't break even until mid-1950s
- Great Depression reinforced bond preference among conservative investors
- Academic research in 1940s–1950s began documenting stock superiority over long periods
- Required 20+ years of data after 1929 to rebuild confidence

### The Great Bull Market of 1982–2000

- Dow Jones Industrial Average: 777 in August 1982 → 11,722 in January 2000
- Total return including dividends: over 15% annually for 18 years
- Best stock market performance in US history
- Driven by falling inflation, declining interest rates, productivity growth
- Technology sector led gains, especially late 1990s **dot-com bubble**

#### Warnings of Overvaluation

- By late 1990s, price-to-earnings ratios reached historic highs
- **Siegel** warned in earlier editions that valuations were stretched
- **Alan Greenspan**'s "irrational exuberance" speech (December 1996) had little impact
- Many analysts justified high valuations with "new economy" arguments
- Traditional metrics suggested stocks were 40–50% overvalued by 2000

#### Late Stage of Great Bull Market 1997–2000

- Tech stocks drove indices to extreme valuations
- **Nasdaq** rose from 1,300 in 1997 to over 5,000 by March 2000
- Price-to-earnings ratios for tech stocks often exceeded 100
- Day trading and retail speculation reached fever pitch
- **Warren Buffett** notably avoided tech stocks, was criticized for being "out of touch"

#### To the Top of the Technology Bubble

- March 2000: Nasdaq peaked at 5,048
- Many unprofitable internet companies valued in billions
- **Pets.com**, **Webvan**, dozens of dot-coms went public with no earnings
- Venture capital flooded into anything with ".com" in the name
- Traditional valuation metrics abandoned in favor of "eyeballs" and "network effects"

#### The Bubble Bursts

- March 2000–October 2002: Nasdaq fell 78% from peak
- Trillions in market value evaporated
- Many dot-coms went bankrupt: **Pets.com**, **Etoys**, **Worldcom**
- Tech-heavy portfolios devastated—some investors lost 90%+
- S&P 500 fell 49% peak to trough
- Took until 2007 for Nasdaq to regain even half its 2000 peak

### From Tech Bust to Financial Crisis

- 2000–2002: tech wreck wiped out speculative excesses
- 2003–2007: housing bubble inflated, financial sector grew to record size
- Easy credit and low interest rates fueled real estate speculation
- **Subprime mortgages** packaged into complex securities
- 2008–2009: **Financial Crisis** caused 57% S&P 500 decline
- Despite two major bear markets in decade, patient long-term investors who held diversified portfolios still earned positive real returns from 2000–2010

