## Chapter 3: Risk, Return, and Portfolio Allocation

### Why Stocks Are Less Risky Than Bonds in the Long Run

> As a matter of fact, what investment can we find which offers real fixity or certainty income? ... As every reader of this book will clearly see, the man or woman who invests in bonds is speculating in the general level of prices, or the purchasing power of money.
> — **Irving Fisher**, 1912

### Measuring Risk and Return
- Risk and return are building blocks of finance and portfolio management
- Once risk, expected return, and correlations specified, modern financial theory helps determine best portfolios
- **Critical difference from physical sciences**: risk/return on stocks and bonds are not physical constants waiting to be discovered
- Cannot run controlled experiments holding all factors constant to find "true" values
- **Paul Samuelson**: "We have but one sample of history"
- Historical analysis necessary for planning, but **underlying factors generating asset prices have remained unchanged**
- Previous chapter showed: fixed-income returns lagged equities substantially AND bonds quite risky for long-term investors due to inflation uncertainty
- **Portfolio allocations depend crucially on investors' planning horizons**

### Risk and Holding Period
- Most meaningful risk description: **worst-case scenario**
- Best and worst after-inflation returns for stocks, bonds, bills from 1802 over holding periods 1-30 years (Figure 3.1)
- Stock returns measured by dividends plus capital gains/losses on broad-based cap-weighted US stock index, reassured after inflation

### Short-Term vs. Long-Term Risk Patterns
- **1-year holding periods**: Stocks clearly riskier than bonds or Treasury bills
  - Best stock return: +66.6%
  - Worst stock return: -38.6%
- **2-year periods**: Similar pattern but narrowing range
- **5-year periods**: Worst stock performance (-11.9% per year) only slightly worse than worst bond/bill performance
- **10-year periods**: Worst stock performance actually **better** than bonds or bills
- **20-year periods**: Stock returns **never fallen below inflation**
  - Bonds and bills fell more than 3% per year below inflation (1961-1981)
  - During that inflationary episode, Treasury bond portfolio (all reinvested coupons) fell nearly 50% in real value
- **30-year periods**: Worst stock return comfortably ahead of inflation by 2.6% per year (1902-1932)
  - Not far below average performance of fixed-income assets

### Never a Negative Real Return on Stocks
- In **220+ years of financial history**, stocks have never delivered negative real return over periods as short as 17 years
- Contrast with bonds or bills
- Might appear riskier to accumulate wealth in stocks rather than bonds over long periods
- **Opposite is true**: safest long-term investment has clearly been diversified portfolio of equities

### The Holding Period Mistake
- Investors often question relevance of 20-, 30-year, or longer holding periods
- **One of greatest mistakes**: underestimating holding period
- Many investors think only about holding periods for particular stock, bond, or mutual fund
- **Critical insight**: Holding period most relevant for portfolio allocation is **length of time investors hold ANY stocks or bonds**, regardless of changes among individual issues

### Probability Analysis (Table 3.1)
- Percentage of times stock returns outperform bond/bill returns over various holding periods
- As holding period increases, probability stocks outperform fixed-income assets increases dramatically
- **1-2 year periods**: stocks outperform bonds/bills only ~3 out of 5 years
- Nearly 2 out of every 5 years, stockholder returns fall behind Treasury bills or bank certificates
- **Short-run underperformance** = primary reason difficult for many investors to stay in stocks
- **10-year horizons**: stocks beat bonds/bills ~75% of the time
- **20-year horizons**: ~85% (84.1% vs. bonds, 88.1% vs. T-bills for 1802-2021)
- **30-year horizons**: 91.6% (1802-2021), 99.3% (since 1871), approaching 100%

### The 30-Year Bond Outperformance Anomaly
- First four editions noted: last 30-year period when long-term bonds beat stocks ended 1861 (onset of US Civil War)
- No longer true due to precipitous drop in government bond yields over recent decades
- 11.03% annual return on long-term government bonds **just passed** 10.98% on stocks for single 30-year period (January 1, 1982 through end of 2011)
- Striking event caused some researchers to conclude stock returns can no longer be counted on to surpass bond returns

### Why Bonds Outperformed 1981-2011
- 1981: interest rate on 10-year US Treasury bonds surpassed 16%
- As interest rates fell, bondholders benefited from both high coupons AND capital gains
- Long-term bond return calculated by selling long-term bond each year, collecting proceeds, reinvesting in new long-term bond
- Result: 7.8% real return on bonds (1981-2011), approximately same as stocks
- 7.8% real return only ~1 percentage point above stocks' 220-year average
- **Double** the average historical real return on bonds
- **Almost three times** the real bond return since 1926

### Current Environment (2021)
- Bondholders face wholly different situation
- End of 2021: yield on nominal bonds ~1.5%, inflation-indexed bonds near -1%
- To garner returns anywhere near stocks, interest rates on nominal bonds would have to fall well below zero (far more than Europe/Japan)
- Yields must become far more negative on inflation-protected bonds

## Standard Measures of Risk

### Random Walk Theory
- 1960s: evidence about stock price unpredictability fostered **random walk theory**
- Random walk: next period's price change completely independent of this period's change
- **Paul Samuelson** (1965): first American Nobel Prize-winning economist published "Proof That Properly Anticipated Prices Fluctuate Randomly"
- Prodigious subsequent work confirmed: statistical behavior of stock prices (at least short run) indistinguishable from random walk

### Random Walk and Portfolio Allocation
- If stock prices are random walks, does NOT follow that long-horizon investor should be more heavily invested in stocks than short-horizon investor
- **Samuelson**: no "time diversification" in market displaying random walk
- Long run: ups do NOT cancel downs to leave investor with more stable return
- Percentage of times stocks beat bonds increases with holding period
- But when there's a loss, could be devastating to portfolio and well-being
- **In random walk world**: percentage of portfolio in stocks does not depend on holding period

### Mean Reversion of Equity Returns
- Data demonstrate: **random walk hypothesis for stock return cannot be maintained for long term**
- Risk (standard deviation of average real, after-inflation annual returns) for stocks, bonds, bills based on 220-year historical sample (Figure 3.2)
- Over 15-20 year holding periods, stocks become **less risky than bonds**
- Over 30-year periods, standard deviation of equity portfolio returns falls to **less than three-fourths that of bonds or bills**
- As holding period increases, standard deviation of average returns falls **nearly twice as fast for stocks as for fixed-income assets**

### Understanding Mean Reversion
- If returns follow random walk, standard deviation of each asset class falls by square root of holding period
- Dashed bars in Figure 3.2 show predicted decline under random walk
- **Random walk predictions do not hold**
- When standard deviation of average stock returns declines faster than predicted by random walk hypothesis = **mean reversion** of stock returns
- Mean reversion does NOT claim total risk of stock portfolio falls as time period extends
- Standard deviation of total stock returns does rise with time, but at diminishing rate
- **"Per year" risk falls as time period becomes longer**

### Historical Development of Mean Reversion Theory
- **James Poterba and Lawrence Summers** (1988): long-term stock returns followed mean-reverting process
- **Eugene Fama and Kenneth French** (1988): long-term stock returns did not appear to conform to random walk hypothesis
- When first edition of *Stocks for the Long Run* published (1994), random walk theory still held sway
- Much skepticism about whether mean reversion actually existed in stock data

### Paul Samuelson's Skepticism (1992)
> Since it takes a long time to duplicate statistical samples of long-term epochs, our confidence in the strength of [mean reversion] must be guarded. Moreover, the size of the alleged effect, particularly after we discount for the possible one-time nature of the 1920-1945 swings of the Great Depression and World War II, may not be great quantitatively. For these reasons, a certain caution toward the new results would seem prudent.

- Emphasized: "We have only one history of capitalism. Inferences based on a sample of one must never be accorded sure-thing interpretations. How did 1913 Tsarist executives fare in their retirement years on the Left Bank of Paris?"

### Shifting Professional Consensus
- Early 1990s: profession split on existence of mean reversion of stock returns
- Consensus shifting by 1999
- **John H. Cochrane** (1999):
> The last 15 years have seen a revolution in the way financial economists understand the investment world. We once thought that stock and bond returns were essentially unpredictable. Now we recognize that stock and bond returns have a substantial predictable component at long horizons.

- Recently indicated: believed over 90% of financial economists would agree equity returns display long-term mean reversion

### Mean Aversion in Bonds
- Stock returns display mean reversion
- Situation **exactly opposite for bonds**
- Figure 3.2: standard deviation of average returns for fixed-income assets does NOT fall as fast as random walk theory predicts
- **Mean aversion** of bond returns
- Once asset's return deviates from long-run average, increased chance it will deviate further rather than return to normal levels
- Mean aversion especially characteristic in **hyperinflations**: prices rise at accelerating pace, rendering paper assets worthless
- Also present in moderate inflations impacting US and developed economies
- Once inflation begins to accelerate, inflationary process becomes cumulative
- Bondholders have virtually no chance of making up losses to purchasing power
- Stockholders holding claims on real assets rarely suffer permanent loss due to inflation

## Volatility Measured from Historical Data

### Challenge to Long-Term Stock Stability
- **Robert Stambaugh and Luboš Pástor**: "Are Stock Really Less Volatile in the Long Run?"
- Claim: standard techniques economists use to estimate long-term risk (computing standard deviations from historical data) **underestimate long-term volatility**
- Factors include: parameter uncertainty, uncertainty of model generating returns
- Additional uncertainty offsets mean reversion shown in historical stock return data
- **Stocks may well be riskier in long run than economists calculated**
- If true, recommendation that long-horizon investors have greater stock portfolio share may not be warranted

### TIPS (Treasury Inflation-Protected Securities) Limitations
- Analysis assumes certain, after-inflation (real) risk-free financial instrument investors can buy to guarantee purchasing power
- **TIPS** safest bonds to protect purchasing power, but have flaws:
  - CPI methodology lags inflation
  - Always possibility government will manipulate index construction to understate inflation for political purposes
  - **Critical flaw**: inflation adjustment applied to TIPS done with calculation of **past, not current** inflation
  - If inflation accelerates (certainly if turns into hyperinflation), TIPS provide very little protection

### Tail Risks and Black Swan Events
- Same caution about interpreting historical risk applies to **every asset**
- All assets subject to extreme outcomes called **tail risks** or **black swan events**
- Some stock markets gone to zero (Russia and China mid-20th century, as Samuelson noted)
- Government bonds become worthless with even greater frequency
- Other wealth forms (land) can be expropriated by governments hostile to private property
- Even gold may be shunned in favor of digital currencies by future generations
- **Equities** (legal claims on productive capital) **more likely to retain real value** in world based on fiat currency constantly facing inflationary threats

## Correlation Between Stock and Bond Returns

### Diversification Through Bonds
- Though bond returns fall short of stocks, bonds may still diversify portfolio and lower overall risk, especially short run
- Particularly true if bond and stock returns **negatively correlated** (prices move in opposite directions)

### Correlation Coefficient
- Diversifying strength measured by **correlation coefficient**
- Ranges between -1 and +1
- Measures comovement between asset's return and rest of portfolio
- **Lower correlation coefficient = better portfolio diversifier**
- Assets with zero or particularly negative correlations with stocks = particularly good diversifiers
- As correlation coefficient increases between asset and portfolio returns, diversifying quality declines

### Historical Correlation Patterns (Figure 3.3)
- Displays correlation coefficient between annual stock and bond returns for three subperiods (1926-2021)
- **1926-1965**: correlation only slightly positive (+0.05)
  - Bonds were fairly good diversifiers for stocks
  - Period included Great Depression (falling economic activity and consumer prices = bad for stocks, good for US government bonds)
- **1966-1997**: correlation jumped to +0.36
  - Bad economic times more likely associated with **inflation**, not deflation
  - Government attempted to offset economic downturns (particularly those caused by OPEC oil price hikes) with expansionary monetary policy
  - Added fuel to inflationary economy
  - Stock and bond prices tend to move together, reducing diversifying qualities
- **1998-2021**: correlation switched to **negative** (-0.28)
  - World markets roiled by: Asian economic/currency upheavals, Japan's deflationary economy, September 11 terrorist events
  - 2008 financial crisis stoked fears of 1930s-style deflation
  - Government bonds became only appreciating asset
  - US government bond market became safe haven for investors fearing economic turmoil and lower stock prices
  - Same situation during Covid-19 pandemic

### Short-Term vs. Long-Term Correlation
- Correlations measured over one-year periods
- Financial crises/pandemics cause investors to rush to safe assets (government bonds stand preeminent)
- Over longer-term periods, **risk to bondholder is inflation**
- Whatever short-term comfort bondholders receive from offsetting short-term stock volatility is **lost in longer term when inflation becomes significant risk**

## Risk-Return Trade-offs

- Modern portfolio theory describes how investors alter risk and return by changing asset mix
- Figure 3.4 displays risks and returns from varying stock/bond proportions in portfolio over holding periods 1-30 years
- Based on historical data from 1802 through 2021

<!-- pp. 101-120 -->

## Chapter 3 (continued): Risk, Return, and Portfolio Allocation

### The Efficient Frontier and Holding Periods

- Figure 3.4 shows **risk-return trade-offs** for holding periods from 1 year to 30 years (1802-2021 data)
- The **efficient frontier** is the curve connecting optimal risk-return combinations from 100% bonds to 100% stocks
- Foundation of modern **asset allocation models**
- Key insight: **optimal allocation depends on holding period**
  - 1-year horizon: minimum risk portfolio is nearly 100% bonds
  - 2-year horizon: still heavily weighted to bonds
  - 5-year horizon: 25% stocks in minimum risk portfolio
  - 10-year horizon: over one-third stocks
  - 20-year horizon: over 50% stocks
  - 30-year horizon: **68% stocks** in minimum risk portfolio

> "Investors should hold a greater fraction in equities than the minimum risk allocations, since the gain in return from adding equities far outweighs the extra risk from doing so."

- Historical data contradicts **random walk theory** of stock prices
- If prices were truly random walks, risk over any period would be a simple function of single-period risk
- In that case, the efficient frontier would not depend on holding period
- But markets don't obey random walks, so **investment horizon must be considered** in portfolio allocation

### Stock-Bond Allocation: Fundamental Considerations

- Primary factors in determining allocation:
  - **Risk preferences**: short-term protection vs. long-term inflation uncertainty
  - For long-term investors with inflation concerns, bond allocation should be lower
  - **TIPS** (Treasury Inflation-Protected Securities) become more important for inflation protection
  - **Age**: mean reversion suggests young investors should hold more stocks
  - Younger investors have higher percentage of **human capital** vs. financial capital
  - Can adjust **labor-leisure choice** if markets perform poorly (work harder to rebuild wealth)
  - Young should have higher proportion in equities due to flexibility

### The 60/40 Retirement Portfolio

- Popular allocation: **60% stocks, 40% bonds**
- Attributed to **William Bengen's** 1994 article "Determining Withdrawal Rates Using Historical Data"
- Bengen used simulations from 1926 historical data
- Recommended optimal allocation: between **50-75% equities** based on client comfort
- Many advisors settled on 60% stocks → 60/40 became common benchmark

#### Evolution from the "Age in Bonds" Rule

- Old rule: percentage in bonds should equal investor's age (very conservative)
- More aggressive than *age in bonds* rule from 1950s-60s, which had no theoretical/empirical basis
- Modern variant: **"age minus 20"** percentage in bonds
  - Example: 60-year-old would hold 40% bonds (60/40 portfolio)
- **Steven Dolvin** and others note current target-date portfolios roughly align with these guidelines

#### Monte Carlo Simulations of Retirement Outcomes

- Figure 3.5 shows probability of running out of money over 30 years
- Two withdrawal scenarios: **4% annually** or **5% annually** (inflation-adjusted)
- Based on historical data 1926-2021:
  - Average real return: **7.12% stocks**, **2.58% bonds**
- **Monte Carlo procedure**: randomizes historical annual returns, runs thousands of simulations
- Includes all bear markets from the past century

**Results at 4% withdrawal rate:**
- Minimum probability of running short: **3.6%** at 50/50 stock-bond portfolio
- All-stock portfolio: 10% probability of running short, but **legacy more than doubles**
- Optimal allocation: between 50/50 and 100% stocks, depending on priorities (avoiding shortfall vs. maximizing legacy)

**Results at 5% withdrawal rate:**
- Minimum probability occurs at **65% stocks, 35% bonds** (13.6% shortfall risk)
- All-stock portfolio: only **3 percentage points higher** risk, but legacy rises almost **40%**

### The Case for 100% Stock Portfolios in Retirement

- **Javier Estrada** studied 19 countries over 110-year period (1900-2009)
- Conclusion: retirement portfolio "fully invested in stocks is a strategy that should be seriously considered by retirees"

- Even **Paul Samuelson**, skeptical of mean reversion, explored 100% stock retirement portfolios
- 1967 *Newsweek* column: "Is 100 percent [in stocks] wise?" → "perhaps yes"
- But suggested investors would "probably sleep better if he only puts 60 percent to 80 percent of surplus savings... into common stocks"
- Samuelson's caveat: "I know older trust officers will raise an eyebrow at this departure from 50/50. But remember, we live in an age of growth and inflation."
- **More than five decades later, inflation threat remains as relevant**

### Forward-Looking Lower Returns

- Figure 3.5 used historical data
- Future returns after 2021 likely to be lower, especially for bonds
- Real yields on bonds declined dramatically over past decades (discussed in Chapter 8)
- Real return for stocks may also be lower (factors in Chapter 10)

#### Figure 3.6: Lower Return Scenario

- Assumes real stock return falls to **4.5% per year** (2.5 percentage points below historical average)
- Forecast real bond return: **-0.5%** (the real yield on 30-year TIPS at end of 2021)
- Still runs Monte Carlo simulations over 30 years with 4% and 5% withdrawal rates

**Striking impact of lower returns:**
- Probability of running out rises for any allocation at any withdrawal rate
- But **counterintuitive result**: don't become more conservative—allocate *more* to stocks
- At 4% withdrawal: minimum probability occurs at **80/20 stock-bond** portfolio
- At 5% withdrawal: minimum achieved at **95-100% stocks**
- Even lowering stock returns by more than bonds, optimal portfolio **shifts strongly to stocks**
- Lower bond returns hurt more than lower stock returns in this scenario

## Conclusion (Chapter 3)

- Short run: stocks riskier than fixed-income assets (no one denies this)
- Long run: **history shows stocks safer than bonds** for long-term investors preserving purchasing power
- Inflation uncertainty inherent in paper money standard means fixed income ≠ fixed purchasing power
- **Irving Fisher** conjectured this over a century ago

> "Historical data show that we can be more certain of the purchasing power of a diversified portfolio of common stocks 30 years hence than we can of the buying power of the principal on a 30-year US Treasury bond."

- Despite slowing inflation over past decade, **huge uncertainty** about future dollar value
- Massive deficits and accommodative monetary policy by central banks create uncertainty
- Drop in forward-looking returns on stocks and especially bonds **argues for even higher stock allocation** in retirement portfolios

## Chapter 4: Global Investing

### Disappointment and Promise

> "Today let's talk about a growth industry. Because investing worldwide is a growth industry. The great growth industry is international portfolio investing." —**John Templeton, 1984**

> "It's been a long time since globally diversified investors could point to their foreign stock allocations with pride." —**Eric D. Nelson, 2021**

- When **John Templeton** spoke to Financial Analysts Federation in 1984, international investing was a "great growth industry"
- 1950s-1960s: United States dominated world economy
- By mid-1960s: US share of world GDP nearly doubled from pre-war levels
- US stocks comprised **75% of world's total equity value**
- Europe and Japan: productive capacity destroyed by WWII, economic turmoil, hyperinflation

#### 1970s Stagflation and 1980s Revival

- 1970s: world suffered **stagflation** from OPEC oil prices and excessive monetary accommodation
- 1980s brought hope for stock investors:
  - **Ronald Reagan** adopted pro-capital stance in US
  - **Margaret Thatcher** revived capitalism in UK

### The Japanese Market Bubble

- **Japan became the first star** of international investing
- Avoided late-1970s inflation, became manufacturing juggernaut
- Produced high-quality automobiles, televisions, innovative electronics (Sony Walkman)

#### The Spectacular Rise

- Japanese stock returns in 1970s-1980s: averaged **10+ percentage points per year above US returns**
- **Nikkei Dow Jones Stock Average**: founded May 16, 1949, set at same level as US Dow
- Rose from 2,000 in 1970 to almost **39,000 by end of 1989**
- Almost **four times** the level of US Dow
- Japanese yen appreciated nearly threefold during the period
- Dollar investors experienced **6,000% return**, 12 times what they would have made in US stocks

#### Extreme Valuations

- Valuations reached stratospheric levels by late 1980s
- **Nippon Telephone and Telegraph (NTT)**: Japanese version of AT&T, had P/E ratio **above 300**
- NTT's market value alone dwarfed aggregate stock values of all but a handful of countries
- Valuations exceeded those in the US tech bubble of 2000

#### Japan Overtakes the US

- By end of 1989: **first time since early 1900s**, US stock market was no longer world's largest
- Japan's market value: **40% of worldwide equities**
- US: just **29%**
- Astounding for a country with half the population and 4% of the landmass of the US

#### Leo Melamed's Warning

- **Leo Melamed**, president of Chicago Mercantile Exchange, traveled to Japan in 1987
- Asked hosts how such high valuations could be warranted
- Response: "You don't understand. We've moved to an entirely new way of valuing stocks here in Japan."
- Melamed knew then Japanese stocks were doomed
- **"It is when investors cast aside the lessons of history that the past comes back to haunt them."**

#### The Collapse

- Bubble burst, Nikkei fell sharply
- Fell to 7,000 in 2008—**less than 20% of peak value** two decades earlier
- By 2020: Japan's share of world equities fell to **7%**
- US share: back over **one-half**

### The Japanese Bubble as Refutation of Long-Run Stock Superiority?

- Some cite Japanese market as refuting the thesis that stocks will always be superior long-run investment
- But there were **glaring warnings**:
  - At peak: Japanese stocks sold for **well over 100 times earnings**
  - More than **three times** the level US market sold at top of its biggest bubble in 2000
- **Mean reversion** eventually dominated
- Figure 4.1: in dollar terms, US Dow caught up to Nikkei by 2021

### Emerging Markets Bubble

- After Japanese collapse, investors turned to **emerging markets**
- Economies like China, India, and others lagged behind US, Europe, Japan but held promise

#### The BRIC Phenomenon

- 2001: **James O'Neill** (Goldman Sachs economist) wrote "Building Better Global Economic BRICs"
- **BRIC**: acronym for **Brazil, Russian, India, China**—countries O'Neill felt would lead new century

- 2003: Two other Goldman economists wrote "Dreaming with BRICs: The Path to 2050"

> "The results [of our research] are startling. If things go right, in less than 40 years, the BRICs economies together could be larger than the G6 (US, Japan UK, Germany, France, and Italy) in US dollar terms... the weight of the BRICs in investment portfolios could rise sharply."

#### BRIC Performance

- Years immediately following O'Neill article were kind to followers of Goldman's advice
- Dow index of 50 BRIC stocks: up **600%** between beginning of 2003 and end of 2007
- Far outperformed 60% rise in S&P 500
- Then BRICs stalled
- Figure 4.2: BRIC Index at end of 2021 was **below the high reached 14 years earlier**
- Over whole period 2003-2021: dollar returns in BRICs lagged or barely matched S&P 500
- **Mean reversion once again ruled**

### The World of Equities 2021

- Figure 4.3: distribution of world equity values as of December 2021
- Total market value of all world stocks: **$70 trillion**
- **United States: 61.2%**
- **Developed Europe: 16.1%** (Austria, Belgium, Denmark, Finland, France, Germany, Ireland, Italy, Netherlands, Norway, Portugal, Spain, Sweden, Switzerland, UK)
- **Japan: 5.5%**
- **Australia and New Zealand: 1.8%**
- **Hong Kong and Singapore: 1.0%**
- **Israel: 0.2%**

#### EAFE

- Countries excluding US comprise **EAFE** (Europe, Australasia, Far East)
- Most popular index of non-US-developed world markets
- EAFE: **24.6% of total world market equity**
- **Canada: 2.9%** (not part of EAFE, though included in some other developed market indices like FTSE)
- Adding Canada to EAFE and US: **total developed world has 88.7%** of world's equity values

#### Emerging Markets

- **MSCI index of Emerging Markets** contains 25 countries
- Five largest:
  - **China: 32%**
  - **Taiwan: 16%**
  - **South Korea and India: each 12%**
  - **Brazil: 4%**
- These five comprise **78% of the index**
- Total market value of emerging markets (December 2021): **$7.8 trillion (11.2% of global equity)**

#### Frontier Markets

- Recently emerged group: **"frontier" markets**
- Developing countries with smaller capitalizations
- **MSCI index of frontier markets**: contains 28 countries
- Largest: **Vietnam (30%)** and **Morocco (10%)**
- Aggregate market value: **$103 billion (0.1% of world's total)**

### International Stock Returns

- Table 4.1: historical risk and returns for dollar-based investors in international markets, 1970-2021 (1989 for emerging markets)
- Over entire period, dollar returns among different regions **do not differ greatly**

**US $ Returns 1970-2021:**
- **World: 10.00%**
- **EAFE: 9.36%**
- **USA: 10.83%**
- **Europe: 9.86%**
- **Japan: 9.07%**

**US $ Returns 1988-2021:**
- **Emerging Markets: 10.50%**

**Correlation with US equity market:**
- **EAFE: 64.80%**
- **Europe: 69.99%**
- **Japan: 38.60%**
- **Emerging Markets: 60.22%**

- Over 51 years: US stocks realized **10.83%** compound returns
- EAFE: **9.36%** return (slightly lower)
- Correlation between EAFE and US: **65%**
- Higher correlation with Europe, meaningfully lower with Japan
- Emerging market returns since 1988: virtually match US, with slightly lower correlation (60%)
- **Imperfect correlations are key reason to maintain international-oriented portfolio**

### Diversification in World Markets

- Given disappointing performance of international investing in 2010s, many considered abandoning global approach
- Three reasons why this logic is faulty

#### Reason 1: Arbitrary Definition of "Foreign" Firms

- Definition of "foreign" firm is arbitrary: based on **headquarters location**, not where it produces or sells
- Example: London-based firm that produces/sells 99% in US is designated a "UK" firm
- Better approach: determine location where country **produces and sells its output**, not headquarters location
- Unfortunately, this approach never caught on
- Despite increase in globalization, geographic investing went in opposite direction
- Most country-based indices purged all foreign firms
- Early 1990s: **Standard and Poor's** announced no new non-US companies would be added to S&P 500
- 2002: removed remaining seven foreign-based firms (Royal Dutch Petroleum, Unilever, etc.)
- Supporters argue: government regulations and legal structures matter, even when most sales/earnings/production come from abroad

#### Trend Toward Industry Factors

- Headquarter influences may diminish if globalization advances
- Evidence it's already happening:
- 2011: **Jose Menchero and Andrei Morozov** research measured "industries versus countries"
- Early 1990s: countries dominated industries by wide margin
- Technology bubble of 2000 thrust industries into forefront
- Even after bubble burst, **industry influences matched or exceeded country influences**
- Since introduction of euro: industry factors much more important within Europe
- For emerging markets: country differences still dominate, but also becoming less important

#### Vision of International Corporations

- Trend likely to continue
- Possibility of **international corporations**: governed by international rules agreed upon among nations
- Headquarters location would be of little/no importance
- **International incorporation standards** similar to worldwide accounting standards from **International Accounting Standards Board (IASB)**
- If international incorporation gained prominence: no meaning to "headquartered country"
- Allocations would be made on basis of **global sectors, or by production/distribution locations**
- Investing only in US would be very narrow
- Even if international incorporations don't materialize, arbitrariness of current classification warns US-only portfolio may be insufficient

#### Reason 2: US Imports and Global Exposure

- Many goods/services bought in US are produced by firms headquartered abroad
- Total US imports at end of 2021: nearly **$3.5 trillion**
- American appetite for foreign automobiles, imported foods, luxury goods is enormous
- If these goods/services are in demand in US, companies that produce them should be in your portfolio

- Some claim investing in US-based stocks alone is sufficient for global exposure
- True: S&P 500 revenues from outside US rising sharply, reaching **41% in 2021**
- Nevertheless: **US still imports far more than it exports**
- Even if America houses growth leaders, doesn't argue for excluding firms that provide products to our economy

#### Reason 3: Diversification

- Third and **most important reason** to hold international stocks: **diversification**
- Ability to spread risk among even greater selection of firms
- Figure 4.4: rolling 10-year returns of US, EAFE, emerging markets
- Markets are **not synchronous**, often move in opposite direction
- **This is the essence of diversification**

<!-- pp. 121-140 -->

## Chapter 4: International Investing (continued)

### Should You Hedge Foreign Exchange Risk?

- **Foreign exchange risk** = two components: domestic risk (local stock price fluctuations) + exchange rate fluctuations between dollar and local currency
- **Currency hedging** offsets unexpected currency movements via contracts or securities that offset foreign currency price changes
- Hedging has costs — depends on interest rate differential between foreign country and dollar rate
- If a currency is expected to depreciate (high inflation), hedging costs can be quite high

#### Historical Example: British Pound
- Even though British pound depreciated from **$4.80 to about $1.60** over past century, the cost of hedging this decline exceeded the depreciation
- Dollar returns to British stocks were **higher for investors who did not hedge** than those who did

#### Long-Term vs. Short-Term Hedging
- **Long-term investors**: hedging currency risk may not be important
- Exchange rates determined primarily by **purchasing power parity** (PPP) — inflation differentials between countries
- Equities as claims on real assets compensate for inflation, thus protect from exchange depreciation caused by higher foreign inflation
- **Short-term investors**: may reduce dollar risk by hedging
- Bad economic news often depresses both stock market AND currency — hedging avoids the latter
- **Policy-driven depreciation**: if central bank lowers currency to stimulate exports/economy, hedged investors benefit without currency losses

#### Empirical Evidence: Emerging Markets
- **1988-2021 period**: Morgan Stanley Capital Index EAFE (non-US developed) return = 5.0% per year
- **Hedged against dollar**: return rose to **5.4%**, standard deviation fell from 16.7% to 14.7%
- Currency hedging **increased returns and reduced volatility** for developing markets over 33-year period

### Sector Allocation Around the World

- **10 Global International Classification (GIC) sectors** tracked across five regions: US, EAFE, Europe, Japan, emerging markets
- **Table 4.2** shows significant sector shifts 2013-2021

#### Technology Dominance in the US
- **Technology sector** dominates US equity valuations despite shift of Alphabet (Google) and Meta (Facebook) from technology to communication services sector in 2018
- Consumer discretionary firms like **Tesla** and **Amazon.com** have huge technology components
- Over **50% of US stocks** were in technology by end of 2021 (including biotech in health care)
- **No other region** approaches US dominance in technology equity valuations
- Major reason why **US valuations exceed rest of world**
- **Communication services sector** also increased significantly from shifting Alphabet, Meta, Disney, Comcast to that sector

#### Energy and Financial Sectors Decline
- **Energy sector**: globally only one-third the percentage it was eight years ago
- **Financial sector**: in 2013 was twice as large as next largest sector (consumer staples); has shrunk significantly though still large among nonglobal firms

### World's Largest Firms

#### 2013 vs. 2021 Comparison (Tables 4.3 and 4.4)
- **2021 top seven US firms**: Apple, Microsoft, Alphabet, Amazon.com, Tesla, Meta, NVIDIA — all heavily involved with technology
- **2013**: four of top seven were NOT in technology — ExxonMobil (#2), General Electric (#4), Johnson & Johnson (#5), Chevron (#6)
- **Five US firms** topped $1 trillion at end of 2021
- Only **one non-US firm** over $1 trillion: Saudi Arabia's **Aramco** (national oil company, went public 2019)
- By end of 2021, Aramco no longer in top tier — eclipsed by Apple and Microsoft
- In US: **11 of top 20 firms** in technology or communications services; elsewhere only 5

#### Valuation Extremes
- **P/E ratio** of seven-trillion-dollar US companies based on estimated 2022 earnings = almost **50**
- Apple, Microsoft, Google averaging modest **30**
- **Amazon.com** at **69**, **Tesla** at **90**
- **Saudi Aramco**: 18 times earnings, dividend yield near 4%
- **Likely many top tech companies will fall from exalted heights**

## Chapter 4: Conclusion

### Globalization Continues Despite Tensions
- Despite geopolitical tensions in 2021, **globalization is not dead**
- Inexorable trend toward integration of world economies and markets will continue
- No country will dominate every market — industry leaders emerge from anywhere on globe
- Strength of management, product lines, marketing more important than firm headquarters location

### Risks of US-Only Strategy
- **US equities = only one-half of world equity market**
- Sticking only to US equities = risky strategy like betting on stocks A through L
- **Only fully diversified world portfolio** will reap best returns with lowest risk

