## Chapter 5: Stock Indexes

### Market Averages

- **Dow Jones Industrial Average** = most quoted stock average in world
- News media often called Dow "the stock market" despite imperfectly describing share price movements
- **S&P 500** (created March 1957 by Standard & Poor's) = uncontested benchmark index for large US stocks
- **Nasdaq** = automated electronic market begun 1971, started as exchange for technology companies
- **"FAANG" stocks**: Facebook (Meta), Amazon.com, Apple, Netflix, Google (Alphabet) — performance of Nasdaq often quoted with Dow and S&P 500 as triumvirate of US stock indexes

### The Dow Jones Averages

#### History
- **Charles Dow** (founder of Dow Jones & Co., publisher of *Wall Street Journal*) created Dow averages late 19th century
- **February 16, 1885**: began publishing daily average of 12 stocks (10 railroads, 2 industrials)
- **May 26, 1896**: Dow Jones Industrial Average created with original 12 stocks (Table 5.1)
- **1889 index** reconstituted and renamed Rail Average (October 26, 1896)
- **1916**: Industrial Average increased to 20 stocks
- **1928**: expanded to 30 stocks (present size)
- **Rail Average** renamed Transportation Average in 1970; composed of 20 stocks for over a century

#### Dow Composition Evolution
- **Early firms** centered on commodities: cotton, sugar, tobacco, lead, leather, rubber
- **Six of original 12 companies** survived in much same form, but none retained membership
- **Only exception**: U.S. Leather Corp., liquidated in 1950s
- Shareholders received $1.50 plus one share of **Keta Oil & Gas**
- **1955**: President **Lowell Birrell** fled to Brazil, looted Keta's assets
- **U.S. Leather** shares (seventh-largest US corporation in 1909) became worthless

#### Computation of the Dow Index
- **Price-weighted index**: prices of component stocks added together, divided by number of firms
- Before computers, this was fastest calculation method
- **High-priced stocks** have much greater impact than lower-priced stocks, regardless of company size
- **February 2022 example**: UnitedHealth Group (9% of index, market price $460) vs. Intel (lowest-priced stock, weight less than 1%)
- **Price-weighting flaw**: becoming more serious as high-priced stocks like Tesla and Amazon.com must be excluded
- **Google's 20-to-1 split** (February 2022) sparked speculation about inclusion in Dow
- Solution: switch to **equally weighted index** not dependent on prices

#### Long-Term Performance Despite Flaws
- **Past 50 years (1971-2021)**: Dow return 11.26% per year beat S&P 500 (11.14%) and Nasdaq (10.85%)
- Despite stodgy image and market value under one-quarter of all US stocks, **Dow Committee chose members wisely**
- Few money managers outperformed the index long-run

### Long-Term Trends in the Dow Jones Industrial Average

- **Figure 5.1**: monthly high/low of Dow from 1885 inception, corrected for inflation
- **Trendline and channel**: statistically fitted, upper/lower bounds = 1 standard deviation (50%) above/below trend
- **Trend slope**: 1.94% per year = average compound rate of Dow appreciation after inflation since 1885
- Dow averages don't include dividends — greatly understate total return
- Average dividend yield on all stocks ~4.3% over period
- **Total annual real compound return** on Dow stocks = at least **6.2% per year** (particularly since Dow dividend yields generally above average)
- Inflation-corrected Dow stayed within channel **three-quarters of the time**
- Breaking out of channel upside (1929, mid-1960s, 2000) = poor short-term returns afterward
- Penetrating channel downside = superior short-term returns subsequently

### When Are Times Really Different?

- Using past price movements to predict future can be misleading
- "This time is different" — sometimes true
- **Longstanding trends broken for good economic reasons**
- Uncorrected for inflation, Dow broke and stayed above trendline in **mid-1950s** (Figure 5.2 inset)
- **Chronic inflation** from shift to paper money standard propelled nominal stock prices justifiably above previous trend
- Those using trendline analysis who failed to plot in **real terms** would have sold in 1955 and never reentered

#### New Channel for Lower Dividend Era
- Stock indexes track only capital appreciation, understate total returns (which include dividends)
- Firms paying ever-lower fraction of earnings as dividends — using difference to buy back shares and invest capital
- Greater part of return now comes through **capital gains instead of dividend income**
- Average dividend yield fallen 1.5 percentage points since 1980
- **New channel drawn in Figure 5.1** with slope 1.5 percentage points higher to represent increased expected growth of capital gains
- End of 2021: Dow slightly above midpoint of new channel

---

## Chapter 5: Value-Weighted Indexes

### Standard & Poor's Index

- **Dow Jones** (1885) not comprehensive — covered at most 30 stocks
- **1906**: Standard Statistics Company formed
- **1918**: began publishing first index weighted by **capitalization (market value)** instead of price
- **Capitalization weighting** = best indication of return on overall market, almost universally used for market benchmarks
- **1939**: **Alfred Cowles** (founder of Cowles Commission for Economic Research) constructed indexes back to 1871 of all NYSE stocks using Standard Statistical Company's market-weighting

#### S&P 500 Launch
- S&P stock price index began **1923**
- **1926**: became **Standard & Poor's Composite Index** (90 stocks)
- **March 4, 1957**: expanded to **500 stocks** → S&P 500 Index
- At that time, S&P 500 comprised ~90% of value of all NYSE-listed stocks
- **500 stocks**: exactly 425 industrial, 25 railroad, 50 utility firms
- **Before 1988**: number of companies in each industry restricted to these guidelines
- **Since 1988**: no industry restrictions on firms selected

#### Base Value and Current Scale
- **Base value = 10** chosen for average S&P Index 1941-1943
- When S&P 500 first published 1957, average share price ($45-$50) ≈ value of index
- Investors could easily identify with S&P 500 changes — one-point change ≈ price change for average stock
- **S&P 500** = 500 largest firms (headquartered in US) by market capitalization
- **Stringent criteria** for admission
- Since index doesn't update continuously, contains some small firms (companies fallen in value, not yet replaced)
- **End of 2021**: total value of all S&P 500 companies = ~$42 trillion
- Constitutes ~90% of value of all US stocks — not much different from percentage when first formulated over half century earlier

### Nasdaq Index

- **February 8, 1971**: revolutionary change in stock trading methods
- **Nasdaq** (National Association of Securities Dealers Automated Quotations) provided up-to-date bid/ask prices on **2,400 leading "over-the-counter" (OTC) stocks**
- Formerly, quotations for unlisted stocks submitted by principal trader or brokerage houses carrying inventory
- Nasdaq linked **500+ market makers** nationwide to centralized computer system

#### Nasdaq vs. Traditional Exchanges
- **NYSE/American Stock Exchanges**: stocks assigned to single specialist maintaining orderly market
- **Nasdaq**: changed how quotes disseminated and made trading issues more attractive to investors and traders
- Initially, **more prestigious to be listed with exchange** (preferably NYSE) than traded on Nasdaq
- Nasdaq stocks = small or new firms recently gone public or didn't meet listing requirements of larger exchanges
- **Many young technology firms** found computerized Nasdaq natural home
- Nasdaq has **lower costs of listing and less stringent membership requirements**
- Some tech firms (Intel, Microsoft) chose **not to migrate to "Big Board"** (NYSE) even when qualified

#### Nasdaq Growth and Dominance
- **Nasdaq Index**: capitalization-weighted index of all Nasdaq stocks, set at **100** on first trading day 1971
- Took almost **10 years to double to 200**, another **10 years to reach 500** (1991)
- First major milestone: **1,000 in July 1995**
- As interest in technology stocks grew, Nasdaq Index accelerated — **doubled to 2,000 in just three years**
- **Fall 1999**: technology stock boom sent Nasdaq into orbit
- Increased from **2,700 (October 1999)** to peak of **5,048.62 (March 10, 2000)**

#### Volume Explosion
- Tremendous increase in volume on Nasdaq following technology stock popularity
- **1971**: volume on electronic exchange = small fraction of NYSE
- **1994**: share volume on Nasdaq exceeded NYSE
- **Five years later**: dollar volume on Nasdaq surpassed NYSE

#### Market Capitalization Milestone
- No longer home of small firms waiting for Big Board membership
- **By 1998**: Nasdaq capitalization already exceeded Tokyo Stock Exchange
- **Market peak March 2000**: total market value of Nasdaq firms = nearly **$6 trillion**
- More than one-half that of NYSE, more than any other stock exchange in world
- **Beginning of millennium**: Nasdaq's Microsoft and Cisco = two largest market values in world
- Nasdaq-listed Intel and Oracle also among **top 10 in market capitalization**

#### Tech Bubble Burst
- Technology bubble burst → trading and prices sunk rapidly
- Nasdaq Index declined from **over 5,000 (March 2000)** to **1,150 (October 2002)**
- Rebounding to **3,000 at end of 2012**
- Trading fell from average **over 2.5 billion shares** when prices peaked to **~2 billion shares in 2007**
- Strong showing of technology stocks in recent years sent Nasdaq to **record of over 16,000 by end of 2021**

### Other Stock Indexes: The Center for Research in Security Prices (CRSP)

#### Origins
- **1959**: **Professor James Lorie** (University of Chicago Graduate School of Business) received request from Merrill Lynch, Pierce, Fenner & Smith
- Firm wanted to investigate how well people had done investing in common stock — could not find reliable historical data
- Lorie teamed with **Lawrence Fisher** to build database of securities data

#### CRSP Database
- With computer technology in infancy, Lorie and Fisher created **Center for Research in Security Prices (CRSP, "crisp")**
- Compiled first **machine-readable file of stock prices dating from 1926**
- Became accepted database for academic and professional research
- Contains all stocks traded on NYSE, American Stock Exchanges, and Nasdaq
- **End of 2021**: market value of **4,317 stocks** in database = over **$50 trillion**

#### Market Concentration
- **Figure 5.2** shows size breakdown and total market capitalization
- **Top 500 firms** (closely mirror S&P 500 Index) = **84.8% of market value** of all stocks
- **Top 1,000 firms** =

<!-- pp. 141-160 -->

## Chapter 5: Stock Indexes (continued)

### Market Concentration in Index Construction

- **Russell index family** captures market comprehensively:
  - Top 500 firms = 55.9% of total market value
  - **Russell 1000** (largest 1,000 firms) = 93.6% of market
  - **Russell 2000** (next 2,000 firms) = 6.3% of market
  - **Russell 3000** (combined) = 99.9% of all US stock value
  - Remaining 1,317 stocks = just 0.1% of market value

### Return Biases in Stock Indexes

**Common misconception**: S&P 500 returns are biased upward because dying firms are deleted and growing firms added.

**Reality**: No statistical bias exists if investors can replicate the index.

- Major indexes announce additions/deletions in advance
- Investors can buy new stocks and sell deleted stocks at known prices
- Post-bankruptcy prices (usually zero) are factored into index calculations
- All major indexes (S&P, Dow Jones, Nasdaq) can be replicated by investors

**Microsoft** example: not added to S&P 500 until June 1994—eight years after going public.

**Tesla** example: not admitted until October 2020, when already a $500+ billion company (fifth largest in index).

- Indexes capture growth of **"fallen angels"** that drop out
- Small stocks are incubators of greatest growth stocks
- Indexes also contain those headed downward

### Why the Average Stock is a Loser While the Stock Market is a Winner

**Henrik Bessembinder** (Arizona State College) research: "Do Stocks Outperform T-bills?"

**Key findings from CRSP database (1926-present)**:
- Slightly more than **50.8%** of individual stocks have positive lifetime buy-and-hold returns
- **Median 90-year return**: only 9.5%, vs. 1,928% for Treasury bills
- Only **27.5%** of individual stocks beat one-month T-bills over 90 years
- Only **4.0%** of individual stocks beat the value-weighted market

> "While a slight majority (50.8 percent) of single stock strategies generated a positive 90-year return, the median 90-year return is only 9.5 percent, compared to a buy-and-hold return on Treasury bills of 1,928 percent."

**JP Morgan confirmation study**: Russell 3000 stocks (1980-2020)
- Median stock returned between **zero and -10%** most of the time
- Includes reinvested dividends

**Mathematical explanation**: Even with zero expected market return, random stock picking leads to underperformance.

**Thought experiment** (symmetric percentage changes):
- 1/4 chance: win-win (100→110→121)
- 1/2 chance: win-lose or lose-win (100→110→99 or 100→90→99)
- 1/4 chance: lose-lose (100→90→81)
- Result: **75% of picks are losing stocks**, even with zero market return
- Adding positive expected returns doesn't change this: still underperform 3/4 of the time

**Critical insight**: Only by buying **all** the stocks do you realize the market rate of return.

**Geometric Brownian motion**: Most popular model for stock price movements assumes perfectly symmetric percentage changes. Even under this assumption, preponderance of losers is expected—**not a necessary condition** for average stock to underperform.

**Implication**: Broad diversification is the **only** guaranteed way to approximate superior long-term stock returns. A narrow portfolio may be a big winner, but usually is a loser.

## Appendix: What Happened to the 1896 Original 12 Dow Industrials?

**General Electric**: Last to exit (2018) after 122 years. None of the original 12 companies or their successors remain in the Dow.

**Fate of the original 12** (market capitalizations as of December 2012):

- **1 stock** (General Electric) kept original name
- **5 became large public companies** in original industries: American Cotton, American Tobacco, Chicago Gas, National Lead, North American
- **1 merged** into U.S. Steel: Tennessee Coal and Iron
- **2 went private** in 1980s: American Sugar, U.S. Rubber
- **1 changed product line** from alcoholic beverages to petrochemicals: Distilling and Cattle Feeding (still manufactures ethanol)
- **1 liquidated**: U.S. Leather (1952)

**American Cotton Oil** → Best Food (1923) → Corn Products Refining (1958) → CPC International (1969) → Bestfoods → acquired by **Unilever** (2000) for $20.3 billion. Market value (2021): ~$100 billion—**most highly valued successor** of original Dow 12.

**American Sugar** → Amstar (1970) → went private (1984) → Domino Foods (1991)

**American Tobacco** → American Brands (AMB, 1969) → Fortune Brands (FO, 1997) → sold tobacco subsidiary to B.A.T (1994) → Beam Inc (BEAM, 2011) → purchased by **Suntory** (2014, Japanese distillery) → remains private

**Chicago Gas** → Peoples Gas Light & Coke (1897) → Peoples Energy Corp. (1980) → bought by WPS Resources → **Integrys Energy Group (TEG, 2006)** → taken over by WEC Energy Group (2015)

**Distilling and Cattle Feeding** → American Spirits Manufacturing → Distiller's Securities Corp. → U.S. Food Products → National Distillers and Chemical → Quantum Chemical Corp. (1989) → purchased by Hanson PLC for $3.4 billion → spun off as **Millennium Chemicals (MCH, 1996)** → bought by Lyondell Chemical (LYO, 2004) → taken over by Dutch firm → **LyondellBasell Industries (LYB, 2007)**

**General Electric (GE)**: Founded 1892. In Dow for 122 years until removal June 2018. Largest market value of any US stock for many months in 1990s and early 2000s. Value declined ~70% during **Jeffrey Immelt** stewardship (2001-2017, followed legendary **Jack Welch**). Immelt removed 2017.

**Laclede Gas (LG)** → Laclede Group, Inc. (retail natural gas distributor, St. Louis) → **Spire Inc. (2017)**

**National Lead (NL)** → NL Industries (1971). Manufactures security products, precision ball bearings, titanium dioxide, specialty chemicals. Still operating but removed from Dow 1916.

**North American** → Union Electric Co. (UEP, 1956, Missouri/Illinois electricity) → merged with Cipsco (Central Illinois Public Service) → **Ameren (AEE) Corp. (1998)**

**Tennessee Coal and Iron** → bought by U.S. Steel (1907) → **USX-U.S. Steel Group (X, 1991)** → changed name back to U.S. Steel Corp. (2002). Removed from index 1991.

**U.S. Leather**: Largest shoe maker early 20th century. Liquidated January 1952, paying shareholders $1.50 plus stock in oil and gas company that became worthless.

**U.S. Rubber** → Uniroyal (1961) → taken private August 1985 → purchased by French company Michelin Group (1990).

## Chapter 6: The S&P 500 Index

> "Nearly 94% of all domestic active stock fund managers had underperformed their respective S&P benchmarks in the past 20 years."
> —**S&P Global**, analysis as of mid-2021

> "The market is a device of transferring money from the impatient to the patient."
> —**Warren Buffett**

### Birth and Evolution of the S&P 500

**Standard & Poor's 500 Index**: Born February 28, 1957. Grew from **S&P Composite Index** (1926), a capitalization-weighted index of 90 large stocks.

**1926 index irony**: Excluded **American Telephone and Telegraph** (world's largest stock), because S&P didn't want one large firm to dominate.

**Postwar correction**: S&P compiled index of **500 largest industrial, rail, and utility firms** trading on NYSE to recognize new firm growth.

**Original composition (1957)**:
- 425 industrial
- 25 rail
- 50 utility firms
- Comprised nearly **90% of total value** of firms on Big Board
- Rapidly became the standard for comparing large-cap US stock performance

**1988 update**: Groupings abandoned to maintain "500 leading companies in leading industries of the economy."

**Continuous updates**: New firms added based on market value, earnings, and liquidity criteria. Firms falling below standards are deleted. ~1,360 new firms added since 1957 inception (average **~20 per year**, constituting **~5% of market value**).

**Highest single-year additions**: 1976 (60 stocks added)—included **15 banks and 10 insurance carriers**. First time financials entered index (previously traded OTC; Nasdaq began 1971).

**2000 tech bubble peak**: 49 new firms added (highest since 1976). First time Nasdaq stocks included.

**2003 post-tech collapse**: Only 8 additions (record low).

### Sector Rotation in the S&P 500

**Dramatic industrial landscape transformation**: Steel, chemical, auto, oil dominated mid-20th century. Today: health care, technology, finance, consumer firms dominate.

**Global Industrial Classification Standard (GICS)**: Created 1999 by S&P + Morgan Stanley. Replaced earlier Standard Industrial Code (SIC) system, which had grown less suited to service-based economy.

**GICS 10 sectors**:
- **Materials**: chemicals, papers, steel, mining
- **Industrials**: capital goods, defense, transportation, commercial/environmental services
- **Energy**: exploration, production, marketing, refining (oil/gas/coal)
- **Utilities**: electric, gas, water, nuclear generation/transmission
- **Telecommunication services**: fixed line, cellular, wireless, bandwidth
- **Consumer discretionary**: household durables, autos, apparel, hotels, restaurants, media, retailing
- **Consumer staples**: food, tobacco, personal products, retailing, hypermarkets
- **Health care**: equipment producers, providers, pharmaceuticals, biotechs
- **Financial**: commercial/investment banking, mortgages, brokerage, insurance
- **Information technology**: software, Internet, home entertainment, data processing, computers, semiconductors

**2016 addition**: **Real estate** sector (REITs) broken out from financials → 11th sector.

**Sector weight changes (1957-2021)**: Dramatic shifts visible in Figure 6.1.

- **Materials**: 26.6% (1957) → 2.6% (2021). By far largest (1957) → one of smallest (2021).
- **Energy**: 20.0% (1957) → 2.7% (2021)
- Combined **materials + energy**: nearly 50% (1957) → only 5.3% (2021)
- **Financial + health care + technology**: only 6% combined (1957) → commanded more than **50% of market value** (2021)

**Sector weight vs. sector return**: Positive correlation exists, but **not strong**.

**Table 6.1 findings**:
- Technology and health care (grew dramatically) did well
- Materials (shrank most) did poorest
- **Energy**: shrank >85%, but returns trailed S&P by <1%
- **Financials and telecoms**: grew rapidly, actually lagged "disappearing" energy sector

**Key insight**: Rising/falling market shares don't necessarily correlate with returns. Change in sector weights reflects change in **number** of firms, not just change in **value** of individual firms. **Valuation** (paying low price relative to earnings) generally more important than growth for long-term investors.

### Oil Sector Performance

**Table 6.2**: Returns of 20 **largest** (not best-performing) original S&P 500 firms (1957).

**Striking finding**: All **9 oil companies** on list finished in top 10. Returns on all but one oil company **beat S&P 500** over subsequent 64 years.

**Top oil performers** (annualized returns, 1957-2022):
1. **Gulf Oil**: 11.90%
2. **Socony Mobil Oil**: 11.66%
3. **Standard Oil Co CA**: 11.52%
4. **Royal Dutch Petroleum**: 11.46%
5. **Standard Oil Co NJ**: 11.24%
6. **Shell Oil**: 11.10%
7. **Texaco**: 11.01%
8. **Phillips Petroleum**: 10.95%

**Methodology note**: Returns calculated assuming shares bought at index creation, all dividends reinvested, spin-offs held with dividends reinvested. Why four firms that went bankrupt had positive total returns: **General Motors** spun off Raytheon; **Eastman Kodak** spun off Eastman Chemical; **Sears** spun off Allstate and Morgan Stanley (so successful that total return to Sears didn't fall far behind S&P 500 despite Sears shares going to zero). **Bethlehem Steel** (no spin-offs) had zero return.

### Performance of S&P 500 Index vs. Original Stocks

**Jeremy Schwartz** (2005) study: "Long-Term Returns on the Original S&P 500 Companies"

**Finding**: Investor who bought and held **original 500 companies** (March 1957) through end of 2006 would have **outperformed actual S&P 500 by nearly 1 percentage point per year**.

**Why did new companies underperform?**

1. Many original companies were **acquired by stronger companies** that became long-term winners
2. Earnings/sales of newer firms often grew faster than older firms, but **price paid was often too high** to generate superior returns

**Critical finding**: Over 1957-2006, only **consumer discretionary sector** added firms that outperformed original firms in the index.

**Mid-2010s shift**: Original companies' outperformance ended when new technology companies (Google, Apple, Amazon.com, Microsoft) began unprecedented run.

**Open question**: Can tech giants' superior performance continue?

