**Table 6.3**: 25 best-performing original S&P 500 firms that survived with corporate structure intact. All outperformed the 10.78% annual return of index itself.

**#1 winner: Philip Morris** (now **Altria Group**)
- 18.02% annualized return (1957-2021)
- Changed name to Altria Group (2003)
- Spun off international division as **Philip Morris International** (2008)
- Introduced **Marlboro Man** (1955)—two years before S&P 500 formation
- Marlboro cigarettes became world's bestselling brand

**Impact of $1,000 invested March 1, 1957**:
- Philip Morris: accumulated to **over $45 million** by end of 2021
- S&P 500 Index: $750,000 accumulation
- **~600 times** the S&P 500 accumulation

**Philip Morris acquisition spree**: Eventually owned **10 other original S&P 500 firms**—General Foods, Del Monte, Standard Brands, National Dairy, Nabisco, among others. Many investors became enormously wealthy from share exchanges. Riding coattails of winners = unexpected windfall for stockholders. (Source of superior returns discussed in detail in Chapter 11.)

### Top-Performing Survivor Firms

**Most successful kept own name, brand, industry**. Two exceptions:

1. **McGraw Hill Publishing** → transformed into S&P Global, spun off book operations
2. **Melville Shoe Corporation** (founded 1892) → most surprising high performer

**Melville Shoe transformation**:
- Shoe companies historically among **worst investments** over past century
- Warren Buffett bemoans 1991 Dexter Shoe purchase
- Melville fortunate to buy few small retail stores specializing in personal health products (1969): **Consumer Value Stores**
- Chain quickly became most profitable division
- 1996: Melville changed name to **CVS**
- Woeful shoe manufacturer → largest and most successful retail pharmacy chain in United States through fortuitous (and serendipitous) purchase

