## Chapter 5 (Notes/References)

### Stock Index Construction

- S&P Dow Jones Indices maintains the index (joint venture majority-owned by S&P Global)
- **General Electric**: Booted out in 2018 after 122 years, was the last original member. Chicago Gas Company became Peoples Energy, Inc., member of Dow Utilities Average until May 1997
- **Stock splits**: Price-weighted index means split stocks have reduced impact on average. Before 1914, divisor left unchanged when stock split, stock price multiplied by split ratio — led to rising stocks having greater weight (akin to value-weighted indexes today)
- **Float adjustment** (2004): S&P went to "float adjusted" weighting excluding shares held by insiders, other corporations, governments. Reduced weight of corporations like Wal-Mart in S&P 500 (many shares owned by Walton family)
- **2021 admission criteria**: (1) Market cap ≥$13.1 billion, (2) liquidity requirements, (3) most recent and last four consecutive quarters of positive as-reported GAAP earnings, (4) US-based. Since 2017, dual-share companies excluded
- **2021 Nasdaq diversity requirement**: Controversial requirement for boards of directors of newly listed firms
- **Double counting admission**: Some double counting of volume in Nasdaq dealer system since dealer buys stock rather than acting as auctioneer (Anne M. Anderson and Edward A. Dyl, *Financial Analysts Journal*, 2007)
- **Dow Jones Wilshire 5000 Index**: Founded 1974, closely related to CRSP indexes
