- Government-sponsored lenders **Fannie Mae** and **Freddie Mac** issued subprime mortgages to unqualified borrowers to promote homeownership
- Nominal vs. real house prices: mortgages denominated in dollars, so nominal index matters more for bond buyers
- Great Depression saw nominal house price declines, but real estate price index fell 25.9% (1928-1932) due to general deflation — CPI fell almost same percentage
- **Robert Rodriguez**, CEO First Pacific, "Absence of Fear" speech (CFA Society Chicago, June 28, 2007)
- **Deutsche Bank Trustee Reports**, October 15, 2007
- **Case-Shiller Home National Home Price Series** data
- **Noelle Knox**, "43% of First-Time Home Buyers Put No Money Down," *USA Today*, January 18, 2006
- **Charles Himmelberg, Chris Mayer, Todd Sinai**, "Assessing High House Prices, Bubbles, Fundamentals and Misperceptions," *Journal of Economic Perspectives* 19, no. 4 (Fall 2005), 67-92
  - Also wrote "Bubble Trouble? Not Likely" (*Wall Street Journal*, September 19, 2005) at peak of housing prices
- Second-home purchase loans ("other than owner-occupied") increased from 8.6% to 14.2% (2000-2004), representing 16% annual growth
  - Actual number doubled: 405,000 to 881,200 loans
  - **Kenneth R. Harney**, Washington Post Writers Group, "Boomer Homeowners Going Back for Seconds," *Chicago Tribune*, April 2, 2006
  - **Keunwon Chung** is statistical economist at NAR

### Financial Crisis Warnings

- **Robert Shiller**, *Irrational Exuberance*, 2nd ed., Princeton University Press, 2005
- **Gary Shilling**, *Forbes* columnist, "End of the Bubble Bailouts," *Forbes*, August 29, 2006
- **Dean Baker**, "The Menace of an Unchecked Housing Bubble," *Economists' Voice* 3, no. 4 (2006)
  - Also: "The Run-Up in Home Prices: Is It Real or Is It Another Bubble?" CEPR, August 2002
  - "The Housing Bubble and the Financial Crisis," *Real-World Economics Review* 46 (March 20, 2008)
- Others who warned: **George Magnus** (senior economic advisor UBS), "What This Minsky Moment Means," *Financial Times*, August 22, 2007
- Land prices argument: only ~20% of residential home costs are land — prices would need to rise fivefold to double home value (not sustainable)
- **Gramlich** died three months before his 68th birthday (published reference to untimely death)

### Federal Reserve & Policy Criticism

- **Alan Greenspan** testimony before Committee of Government Oversight and Reform, October 23, 2008
- Greenspan's EMH defense: markets self-correct, "irrational exuberance" speech (December 1996) didn't reflect belief prices always right
  - EMH implies prices not "obviously wrong" in exploitable way
  - Widespread disagreement existed about housing paradigm shift justifying higher prices
- **John G. Taylor** (Stanford professor), *Getting off Track: How Government Actions and Invention Caused, Prolonged, and Worsened the Financial Crisis*
  - Blamed Greenspan's Fed for keeping rates too low
- Others blaming Fed: **Gerald O'Driscoll Jr.** (Cato Institute), **David Malpass** (Encima Global), **Ron Paul** (steadfast Fed critic)
- BBC news sourcing Federal Reserve, Bank of England, SIFMA data

### Mortgage-Backed Securities & Bank Failures

- Structured credit funds: "High-Grade Structured Credit Strategies Enhanced Leverage Fund" (fancy names)
- **Bear Stearns** and **Citibank** tried insulating via off-balance sheet special investment vehicles
  - Defaults mounted, legal counsel recommended taking mortgages back onto balance sheets
- Government debt without central bank backing not "riskless" — illustrated by Eurozone crisis 2011-2012
- **Asset-Backed Commercial Paper Money Market Mutual Fund Liquidity Facility** created
- Non-interest-bearing accounts (demand deposits) critical for payment systems — Fed prioritized maintaining function
- FDIC trust fund ratio (designated deposit ratio) was 1.35% in 1996, fell below 1.0% by September 2008

### Academic & Institutional Background

- **Bernanke** earned economics doctorate eight years after Siegel (same MIT specialty)
  - MIT known as "Keynesian" school, but monetarist thought and monetary history well-covered
- Federal Reserve discount rate policy: 12 USC 343 (Glass-Steagall Act provisions)
  - Added by July 21, 1932 (47 Stat. 715)
  - Amended August 23, 1935 (49 Stat. 714)
  - Amended December 19, 1991 (105 Stat. 2386)
- **Henry M. Paulson Jr.**, *On the Brink*, Hachette Book Group, 2010
- **Peter Chapman**, *The Last of the Imperious Rich: Lehman Brothers 1844-2008*, Penguin Group, 2010, 262-263
- **Bernanke** (Republican) quote at Kansas City town hall (July 2009): "I was not going to be the Federal Reserve Chairman who presided over the second Great Depression. I had to hold my nose...I'm as disgusted as you are [about bailouts]"
  - Associated Press, July 27, 2009, "Bernanke Had to 'Hold My Nose' over Bailouts"

### Economic Data & Measurement

- **Milton Friedman and Anna Schwartz**, *A Monetary History of the United States, 1867-1960*, Princeton University Press, 1963
- GDP decline would be greater if quarterly data available — quarterly GDP not available until 1946
- **Joseph Swanson and Samuel Williamson**, "Estimates of National Product and Income for the United States Economy, 1919-1941," *Explorations in Economic History* 10, no. 1 (1972)
  - Also: **Enrique Martínez-García and Janet Koech**, "A Historical Look at the Labor Market During Recessions," Federal Reserve Bank of Dallas, *Economic Letter* 5, no. 1 (January 2010)
- Price decline (July-December 2008) occurred as oil prices plummeted
- 1/0.73 calculation = 37% increase needed to recover from 27% decline
- Great Recession moderating factors (vs. Great Depression):
  - FDIC deposit insurance
  - Generous unemployment compensation
  - Automatic tax revenue reduction as incomes/assets fell (cushioned disposable income decline)
  - Federal government spending expansion
- 1974 and 2008 stock declines almost identical in real terms (1973-1974 had greater inflation)

### Market Volatility & Crisis Comparisons

- VIX Index hit almost 170 on October 20, 1987
  - Reached 50 in 1997 (Asian crisis)
  - Hit 50 in 1998 (Long-Term Capital Management collapse)
  - Spiked in 2001 post-9/11
  - Bottomed at previous bear market low (2002)
- Global market declines (dollar terms): all fell 50%+
  - Italy, Finland, Belgium, Russia, Greece, Austria: 70%+ decline
  - Ireland: 80%+ decline
  - Post-March 2009 rally: many European markets hit new lows during euro crisis
  - **Athens Stock Exchange Index**: fell 92.7% (September 1999 to June 2012)
- **JPMorgan Index** of emerging market currencies: fell ~19% relative to dollar (October 2007-March 2009)
  - Local currencies: emerging markets fell ~53% (similar to developed markets)
- **General Growth Properties**: fell from $20/share (Lehman bankruptcy) to under 20 cents (loan repayment demands)
- **Morgan Stanley Internet Index**: fell 96% (January 2000-March 2002)
- By September 2012 (2.5 years post-bottom): stocks still down 89%, 95%, 98% from highs
- Banks avoiding crisis (Wells Fargo, J.P. Morgan) rebounded to new highs by 2013
  - Lost 80% and 70%+ at bottom, respectively

### Inflation & Deflation Dynamics

- Great Depression: real earnings decline less severe due to price level deflation
- **LIBOR** scandals and mispricing (early 2020s) led to replacement by other short-term indicators
  - **Secured Overnight Funding Rate (SOFR)** emerged as leading substitute by 2022

## Chapter 24: Post-Crisis Recovery & Monetary Policy

### Bull Market Duration & Fiscal Response

- Longest bull market: 13+ years (December 4, 1987 to March 24, 2000)
  - Withstood 19.92% decline in 1990
- 2021 economy recovery after Covid: conservative opposition resuscitated against further spending
  - Democrats narrowly controlled Congress, passed **$1.9 trillion American Rescue Act** (March 2021)
  - **$700 billion bipartisan infrastructure bill** passed November 2021
  - Future spending plans deadlocked in Congress as of writing

