### Index Fund History & Index Effect

- Five years before **Vanguard 500 Index Fund**, **Wells Fargo** created equally weighted index fund (**Samsonite**) — assets remained small
- **Roger J. Bos**, *Event Study: Quantifying the Effect of Being Added to an S&P Index*, McGraw-Hill, Standard & Poor's, September 2000
- **David Blitzer and Srikant Dash**, "Index Effect Revisited," *Standard & Poor's*, September 20, 2001
  - Also: **Hanis Boston and Aye Soe**, "What Happened to the Index Effect? A Look at Three Decades of S&P 500 Adds and Drops," S&P Global Research, September 2021
- Most indexes adjust quantity of shares by excluding **insider holdings** (large positions by insiders/governments)
  - Government holdings especially large in emerging economies
  - Called **float-adjusted shares** (float = readily available shares)
- Disclosure: author is senior investment strategy advisor at **WisdomTree Investment, Inc.** (fundamentally weighted ETF issuer)

### Fundamental Weighting

- Fundamentally weighted indexes construction:
  - If *E* = total dollar earnings of chosen stocks, and *E_j* = earnings from firm *j*
  - Weight given to firm *j* in fundamental index = *E_j/E* (share of total earnings)
  - Higher than market value share in cap-weighted indexes
- **Robert D. Arnott, Jason C. Hsu, Philip Moore**, "Fundamental Indexation," *Financial Analysts Journal* 61, no. 2 (March/April 2005)
- **Henry Fernandez**, "Straight Talk," *Journal of Indexes* (July/August 2007)
- **Robert Jones**, "Earnings Basis for Weighting Stock Portfolios," *Pensions and Investments*, August 6, 1990
- **Paul C. Wood and Richard C. Evans**, "Fundamental Profit-Based Equity Indexation," *Journal of Indexes*, second (2003)
- **Robert D. Arnott, Jason C. Hsu, Philip Moore**, "Fundamental Indexation," *Financial Analysts Journal* 61, no. 2 (2005)

